Untitled Page 32

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/09/2012 11:24 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Sunday, January 1, 1950

Still below par from a cold, but at least out of bed. Did a lot of miscellaneous work to catch up. Put the recently bound books away.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/09/2012 11:25 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Monday, January 2, 1950

Feeling better today. Worked all day and late into the evening on the [reptile] library. Selected a lot more material to be bound (it still requires instructions to binder, which will take a day to prepare). Rearranged a lot of books. A lot of work could be put in on the library. A day like today shows how much it has been neglected. I could spend all my spare time just writing for separates, but I have no idea of doing anything like this. Having spent most of my vacation time form 1922 to 1925 on the library, I woke up and decided to go after herpetological literature. I have no idea of back-tracking now, but it pains me to see so good a library suffer. At least I haven't passed any good items offered for sale, but the pamphlet foundation has suffered; and many items required to complete papers that were published in sections, are missing.

Thursday, January 12, 1950

Drove to LA this morning with GG, Phil and Ruth Badrow.

Left a lot of books at the Long Beach Bindery.

Went to a show - Inside USA - with Beatrice Lilley in the afternoon.

Strained my back either late yesterday of this AM. shouldn't have made the trip.

Had expected to go on to San Francisco, to a State Chamber of Commerce Meeting on the Lark this evening but didn't go

Saturday, February 25, 1950

Another reading of the Chionactis paper. Picked up some loose cards and rearranged in logical form. Now appears finished. Will let it sit for a month and then give it another look.

Went to a meeting at the Zoo Board at noon.

Saturday, March 11, 1950

Worked all day and late into the evening on length and cleared up quite a lot of material.

Turned aside to study some of the new subspecies and their validity, an item to which a lot of time will have to be given some day. Made good progress on this as far as a preliminary survey goes.

Spent the entire day on taxonomy. Necessary to have the data so I could check important specimens, if I should go East.

Left for San Francisco on the 3:45 train.

Thursday, March 23, 1950

In San Francisco all day. Went to a Light & Power Council meeting in the morning. Spent a couple of hours in the Stanford Medical Library in the afternoon and picked up a few items. Not much luck.

Recd from Ted Myers
3 helleri large
1 from 2 mi S. of Capistrano
2 = US 101 near Las Flores

Friday, March 24, 1950

Spent the day at Berkley, mostly in the Library and cleared up a few troublesome items. Also checked over their recent rattler acquisitions and picked out some Mexican material to be sent me. Worked over there from 9:30 AM to 6 P.M.

Saturday, April 1, 1950

Worked all day on the Rattlesnake Check List and made good progress. There are many involved nomenclatorial problems to solve.

Went to Chuck Leigh's for dinner.

Trip of Shaw and Schwenkmeyer to Lower California

Sunday, April 2, 1950

Worked up to near train time (3:45) on the rattler check list and included the first draft, not including geographical ranges.

Left on the 3:45 for San Francisco
________________________________________________________________
Shaw and Schwenkmeyer trip toLower Calif. Cont.

1 anniella pulchra caught at Colonia Guerrero

San Quintin. Worked hard for Anniella in dunes. Got only one. cacti

Monday, April 3, 1950

Shaw and Schwenkmeyer trip continued.

Left El Rosario for the beach at 7:30 AM.
Hunted for anniella at Punta Baja or slightly to the south. Got 10 geronimensis
1 P. c. annectens S DOR a mi. E. of Rosario. Saved scattered brush and sand hills.
1 C. r. ruber COR 8 mi. E. of Rosario 2:15 P.M. Dry wash, heavy cacti and

Tuesday, April 4, 1950

Shaw and Schwenkmeyer Expedition Continued

Hunted around San Fernando Mission until 11 AM. Got only a couple of Utas and 1 T. o. hammondii in a pond. There are both Hyla and Bufo tadpoles in the pond.
Saw several C. t. tigris, C. d. gabbii, and a couple of C. hyperythrus. Left here at 11:25.
1 Horned toad COR 11:55 AM. 6 mi. E. of Mission San Fernando. Sandy desert, creosote bush, and low scattered bushes.
1 P. platyrhinos COR 12:45. On a rock. Creosote & burro weed. Sandy desert. 24 mi. N. of Catavina
1 P. coronatum COR 24 mi. N. of Catavina 12:50
1 P. coronatum COR 19 mi. N. of Catavina 1:30
Hunted for Xantusias in good granite 15 mi N. of Catavina. No luck Got
1 C. m. pyrrhus S COR 19 mi. N. of Catavina.
Reached Catavina at 4 P.M. Turned around and found a camp site 2 miles to the north.
Went out in the evening and got 1 Bufo punctatus, 9 Hyla regilla, and 7 Hyla arenicolor.

Wednesday, April 5, 1950

Left the cap 2 mi. N. of Catavina at 7 AM. Hunted in a palm canyon to the east. Saw Streptosaurus, Uta, and Urosaurus. Saw few Callisaurus and Sauromalus droppings but no chucks.

In early evening got 3 Phyllodactylus ruberculosus under rocks, but no Xantusia. Plenty of good granite flakes here. Much like Jacumba and Mt. Spring's Grade.

Got 9 Urosaurus spp.
3 Uta stans.

Saturday, June 3, 1950

At the New York Public Library from 9:10 to 4:45. Cleared up a number of obscure items reducing the want list to a new low. Had been told the rare book room closed at 5, whereas a new time schedule had gone into effect that day and it actually closed at noon. Had quite a time getting 2 items therefrom, but finally made it.

Went to dinner with the Bogerts tonight.

Friday, June 9, 1950

At the Library of Congress today from 9 to 3. Assisted by Allan Heyneman, who saved me a lot of time by doing all the searching and requisitioning. I made fine progress and brought the list of bibliographic wants down to the lowest point in years.

Even went through "Outdoor Life" and cleaned up all the numbers not yet seen during the time that Bevan edited the "Snake Lore" department.

Left westward at 5:25 P.M.

Saturday, June 10, 1950

Visited the St. Louis Zoo this afternoon -- that is the reptile house. Was in St. Louis from 1:10 to 4 P.M. The best thing they had was a durissus. Certainly the spinal ridge and scale tuberculations make it a strange looking creature, compared with other rattlers; this differences are much accentuated in life.

Friday, June 16, 1950

Started for the Salt Lake City convention of the Pacific Division, AAAS at 1:15 P.M. with GG Cool and cloudy.
56 miles in S. D. Co.

1 Gopher L DOR 4 mi. S. of Murrieta, Riv. Co, grass
1 Gopher M DOR 4 mi. S. of Murrieta, Riv. Co, grass
1 Whiptail SOR 8 mi. SW of Baker, S.B.. Co,

The first and only lizards seen were in the neighborhood of Cronise, S.B. Co. at about 6:30 P.M.; probably callies, but couldn't be sure. It was hot between Barstow and Baker, where we arrived at 7. About 96 degrees. Dusk at Shoshone, Inyo Co. We left there at 8:30 after writing postals. Reached Death Valley Junction, Inyo Co at 9:20. It was then quite dark. New moon and little wind. A perfect night but little to be seen.

1 Platyrhinos DOR 1 mi. N. of Death Valley Junction, Inyo Co. Saved (1)
1 Phyllorhynchus COR 2 mi. N. of Death Valley Junction, Inyo Co. 9:20, 80 degrees F.

Reached Beatty, Nye Co, Nevada at 11:05 It was cool and pleasant. Put up at the Wagon Wheel Motor Court.

California and Nevada on P.D.S.Time. Miles evening drive 80; time 2 hr 55 min. Miles today 389.

Monday, June 19, 1950

At the Salt Lake Convention of the Pacific Division AAAS.

Registered in the morning and circulated around among the herps.

Spent the afternoon in the University of Utah reptile collection making a record of their specimens.

Had a dinner meeting of the Executive Committee of the Pacific Division.

At 8 went to the annual meeting of the Governors of the ITH Society. This lasted until about 11. It was very dull; fussing over technicilities.

Among those seen were Stover, Bogent, Dowling, Hartweg, Margaret Storey, Myers, Woodbury, W. Tanner, Jameson, Maslin, Stebbins, V. M. Tanner, Netting, Fitch, Taylor, Savage, Norris, Zweifel, Walter Brown, Mulaik, Ross Hardy, Anita Daugherty, Hart, and Edward Raney.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/13/2012 06:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

C#-

At the Salt Lake Convention of the Pacific Division, AAAS.

Presided at a symposium entitled "The Westward Migration and its Consequences". This lasted from 9 until about 11:30. I missed one herp. paper at the I & H sessions.

In the afternoon at 1:30 went to the session of the Herpetologists League and heard a series of papers on variety of subjects, including 7 on Woodbury's Rattler den. Had to leave at 3:45 so missed the discussion on the latter.

At 4 P.M. stood in line at a reception at the residence of A. Ray Olpin, President of the University.

At 6 attended another dinner meeting of the Executive Committee of the Division.

At 8:30 presided at the evening address of Dr. O. J. Murie, Director of the Wilderness Society on "Saving the Western Wilderness".

pamg

Date is incorrect. Correct date is Tuesday, June 20, 1950

Wednesday, June 21, 1950

At the Salt Lake City Convention of the Pacific Division, AAAS.

Attended at 7:30 breakfast meeting on the future of the Herpetologist's League & Herpetologica.

From 9 to 12 combined sessions of the I & H Soc. and Herp. League.

This continued in the afternoon from 1:30. I had to leave for a meeting of the Executive Council of the Pacific Division from 4 to 6, where I presided. President Adams of the AAAS made an interesting talk.

Went to the Herpetologists dinner at 6 and at 8:30 make the presidential address.

Saturday, June 24, 1950

Started home from Las Vegas at 10:10

1 Red Racer S DOR Itelendale, S.B. Co brushy desert
1 Gopher L DOR Rainbow
1 Banded King L DOR 7 mi. S. of Rainbow. Brush

Reached home at 6:05. Miles today 346
Miles in SD County 56
Total miles for the trip 1910.

The trip was a success as far as the meetings and contacts were concerned, but as a collection trip it was very poor.

This was a most disappointing evening drive. The road appeared to be a good one, not much travel. Wind mild. 1/2 moon. Temp. about 80 to 84 degrees most of the time. While I probably drove too fast to see a very small snake, I certainly would not have missed one of any size. They just weren't out.

Saturday, July 15, 1950

Spent the morning taking a preliminary look at the snake-bite material with the idea of making an up-to-date index or outline for this chapter. There is a very large amount of material available and it may prove the longest chapter of all. I got some material organized but did not get the outline even started.

Spent the afternoon and evening carefully surveying the specimen availability situation covering lepidus and triseriatus especially with regard to ordering material from USNM and CNHM. Finished this OK and got the picture well in mind.

Didn't do too well today a/c suffering from hay fever or something like it.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/18/2012 04:51 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Sunday, July 16, 1950

Spent the entire day and evening on the molossus - durissus - basiliscus problem. Looked at a lot of specimens trying to find new characters of interest and value for the keys. Not much luck.

Have decided definitely not to try to segregate the Texas molossus population. The neck stripe looks good but too many specimens from elsewhere are indeterminate.

Studies the durissus - terrificus, basiliscus - molossus, durissus - totonacus and similar problems and reduced the extent of future problems.

Did fairly well today in spite of feeling pretty punk,

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/18/2012 05:08 PM
  • pamg 11/18/2012 05:06 PM
  • pamg 11/18/2012 05:06 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Monday, July 17, 1950

Today for the first time I got the idea of writing a paper with a title something like: "A Taxonomic Preview of Some Rattlesnakes of the Mexican Mainland" to include some of the data I am picking up on the forms I am investigating for the key and check list. I am gathering the data anyway and it won't take too long to put it in the form of a paper. Besides it will co-ordinate my thinking and conclusions.

The shipments are beginning to arrive; 2 large ones today.

  • pamg 11/18/2012 05:17 PM

Saturday, July 22, 1950

Worked all day and evening (except for a party late in the afternoon) on the triseriatus - pricei relationship. A fairly productive day. Reached the conclusion that they don't intergrade. Also worked out the omiltemanus relationships and decided to recognize 2 subspecies, omiltemanus and gloydi. Trausversus still unseen.

Went to a zoo directors meeting this noon. This took nearly 2 hours.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/18/2012 05:19 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Sunday, July 23, 1950

Spent the entire day and evening on triseriatus and made progress, although I have to wait for more material and more counts and measurements before a final decision can be made. There seems to be a large rattle northern form with fewer spots, and a small rattle southern form with more spots. There should be a better break than that based on the shape of the spots. Dont know whether they overlap or intergrade.

Finished overhauling the Chionactis paper today; then went back to the rattlers. Took care of a lot of records and made a number of scale counts. When del Campo's specimens have arrived I will await no more material or data, but will clean up one species at a time as rapidly as possible.

Wednesday, November 29, 1950

Spent the morning from 8:40 to 11:40 at the Stanford Natural History Museum. Saw Margaret Stoney, Savage, Leviton and others. Counted a few of Savage's Sonoran rattlers. He will send me the rest.

He thought road collecting in the Hermosillo - Guaymas area would be best in the spring, not summer.

Sidewinders occur in a 20 mile sand hill belt along the coast. One was found in the thatched roof of an abandoned shack.

Spent the afternoon in Chickering and Gregory's office and out at the Commission discussing preferred stock issue.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/24/2012 03:34 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:56 PM

Went over the U.C. arriving at 3 and stayed until 7:45. Saw Murray. Spent the rest of the time in the Library and cleared up several items.

Left on the Lark tonight.
